ce:section.ce:para:
Understanding the mechanism underlying the fluorescence emission is the foundation for the rational design and synthesis of red CDs. So far, researchers have proposed several theories to explain the luminescence mechanism, including surface/molecular state [20,21], carbon core state, size effect, and cross-linked enhanced emission (CEE) effect. For the majority of CDs, luminescence is influenced by both their carbon core and surface state. Particularly, longer wavelength emission of red-emitting CDs could be achieved by adjusting factors such as precursor selection, solvent change, and reaction temperature and time optimization, which in turn affect surface oxidation, lager conjugated structures, and heteroatom doping in the carbon nucleus. In recent years, a series of red CDs have been prepared from cheap carbon precursors (e.g., phenylenediamine, citric acid, and phenol) via the bottom-up method [22–24]. However, most of the developed red CDs are water-soluble,[

                        25–27

                     ] have a low fluorescence quantum yield (QY), and the emission of the CDs typically occurs below 650 nm, which limits their application in plant growth. Furthermore, CDs purification is often accomplished via column chromatography, which is time-consuming, yield-limited, and difficult to manage. Therefore, the development of red-emission CDs with exceptional fluorescence properties and ease of manufacture is extremely desired.
